  "texts": [
    "A significant portion of the datasets usedTABLE IV: Overview of publicly available speech-based understanding datasets.",
    "The table categorizes datasets into three groups: SLU, Question Answering about Spoken Content, and Spoken Question Answering.",
    "Dataset Name Input Modality Output Languages Size / Duration Year Traditional SLU Tasks ATIS3 [144], [145] Spoken utterance + transcript Intent + slots English 11k utterances 1990 SNIPS (spoken) [1] Spoken command recordings Intent + slots English 5.9k utterances 2018 CATSLU [146] Spoken utterance Intent classification Chinese 16k utterances 2019 SLURP [147] Spoken utterance Intent + slots English 72k utterances 2020 Speech-MASSIVE [148] Spoken utterance Intent + slots 12 languages 83k utterances 2024 SQA: Question Answering about Spoken Content TOEFL-QA [149] Spoken lecture + text question (MCQ) Text (choice) English 963 QA pairs 2016 Spoken SQuAD [150] Spoken passage + text question Text span English 42k QA pairs 2018 ODSQA [151] Spoken document + spoken/text question Text span Chinese 7k QA pairs 2018 Spoken-CoQA [152] Spoken passage + spoken questions Text (free-form) English 40k QA turns 2022 NMSQA [153] Spoken passage + spoken question Text span English 92k QA pairs, 335h audio 2022 CORAAL-QA [154] Spontaneous long-form audio + text query Text span English (AAVE) 143 interviews, hundreds of QA pairs 2024 AIR-Bench [155] Speech/Music/Sound/Mixed + text query Text (choice/freeform) English 18.6k VMCQ + 2k QA pairs 2024 MMAU [156] Speech/Music/Sound + text query Text (choice) English 10k VMCQ 2025 MMAR [157] Speech/Music/Sound/Mixed + text query Text (choice) English 1k VMCQ 2025 SQA: Spoken Question Answering SD-QA (TyDi) [158] Spoken question + text context Text span 5 languages 68k spoken questions 2021 SQuAD-SRC [159] Spoken question + text context Text span English (6 accents) 10k spoken questions 2023 HeySQuAD [160] Spoken question + text context Text span English 173k spoken questions 2024 SpokenNativQA [161] Spoken question Text answer English, Arabic 33k spoken questions 2025to train Speech LLMs consists of audio-text pairs, which are readily available from many traditional single-task datasets.",
    "In addition to these audio-text pairs, tasks like speaker diarization and keyword spotting often include additional metadata, such as timestamps and speaker labels, to enhance task performance.",
    "Rather than being limited to single-task datasets, multitask datasets with rich metadata are also widely used, enabling training across multiple tasks."
